children.subject:
126+127+189 isnt enough to take ee47e, you can get rejected from taking it even with ee 120, ee123, eecs 106a, cs170, etc in addition to 126+127+189 (Ik a few people with this experience (had A/A+s in all of the above) who tried)

I think everyone who was able to take it that ik had taken upper div physics classes like 111a (circuits), physics 188 (ML), physics 89 (linalg). Depends on the prof as well but ik in the past few semesters the professors have strongly believe that students have a lot to learn still.

Doesnt hurt to try but id be surprised if you got it (unless there are different profs then it would make sense).

Something polite like "Looking at the EECS 16B course website, an overwhelming majority of the material seems to have been covered in my previous courses <list courses here and put what they mean wrt 16b in parenthesis>. I was just wondering if there are any alternative options for me. I completely understand the importance of this course and have full trust that the EECS department has students' best interests in mind with curriculum design, but given some of my previous coursework, I would like to explore alternative paths, like perhaps EECS 47E. Thank you for your time."

The class does exist for some people so if you have that circuits overlap as well i would be surprised if you don't get in
